This paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) category as it proposes a kinematics-constrained localization system for a mobile robot. It also involves the integration of visual and inertial sensors, which falls under the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category. The paper also discusses the use of sliding-window bundle adjustment, which is a common optimization technique in machine learning and optimization, and thus could be categorized under Learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves the estimation of time-varying parameters, which could fall under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category. Finally, the paper involves the use of observability analysis, which is a common technique in control theory and estimation, and thus could be categorized under Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI).
